http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value: This ontology provides a generic representation of resources that contain core properties generic across all transportation uses. We take the view presented in the TOVE model (Fadel, Fox, and Gruninger, 1994) that "...being a resource is not an innate property of an object but a property that is derived from the role the object plays with respect to an activity". The definition of  a resource is dependent on its participation in an activity occurrence, so the Resource ontology is in fact an extension of the Activity ontology. In this sense, Resources are a class of manifestations, so that rather than have a specialized Resource-perdurant (PD) class, a Resource is a manifestation of some other perdurant class in the ontology. For example, an instance of a Vehicle that is a manifestation of some VehiclePD may also be an instance of a resource, whereas some other instance of a Vehicle that is some later manifestation of the same VehiclePD may not be a Resource, or it may be a different Resource.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value:
Developed as part of the overall iCity ontology effort, the iCity-Resource ontology is designed to capture concepts related to resources.
		Changes from previous version: 
		-modifications required for update to iCity-Activity ontology
		-removed ResourceType class (much like activities, types of resources shall be captured via various classes of resources)
		-Resource consumedBy or usedBy only Activity
		-Resource participatesIn min 1 Activity
		-Resource usedBy only Activity
		-NonDivisibleResource usedBy exactly 1 Activity
		-removed consumedInOccurrence, usedInOccurrence
		-old axioms relating Resources to ActivityOccurrences removed

http://www.w3.org/ns/adms#relatedDocumen.@value: Under development. Please see report on iCity Ontology v1.

http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/descript.@value:
A Resource is a generic representation of some Thing that can be "used" in an Activity.
A Resource may have some Location, amount or availability, according to the definition of the Manifestation or TimeVaryingEntity.
A Resource must be classified as some Resource Type.
A Resource may participate in some Activity Occurrence.
A specific Resource may be used in or consumed in some activity occurrence.
Added for organizational purposes, to identify all properties defined in the Resource ontology.
Added for organizational purposes, to identify all classes defined in the Resource ontology.
